:"Ringstead, Northamptonshire, England","Cîteaux, Cote d'Or, Bourgogne, France":"Cîteaux, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France","Farley Green, Surrey, England":"Farley Green, Surrey, England","Great Addington, Northamptonshire, , England":"Great Addington, Northamptonshire, England","Farley Green, Albury, Surrey, England":"Farley Green, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","<, Albury, Eng>":"Albury, Hertfordshire, England","Huntingdon, Le Haut-Saint-Laurent, Quebec, Canada":"Huntingdon, Le Haut-Saint-Laurent, Quebec, Canada","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Arrow","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Arrow in Warwickshire or Arrowe in Cheshire. The first takes its name from the Arrow river, a Celtic or pre-Celtic term meaning ‘stream’; the second, recorded <i>c.</i> 1245 as <i>Arwe</i>, is from Old Norse <i>erg</i> ‘shieling’. Perhaps sometimes from Harrow on the Hill in Middlesex, and therefore a variant of   Harrow   with loss of initial <i>H-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Harrow","meanings":["English: habitational name from Harrow (Middlesex), which was named in Old English with <i>hearg</i> ‘(pagan) temple’.","Scottish: habitational name from Harrow near Mey (Caithnesshire)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":31,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":40,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":51,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":53,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":67,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1670184,"age":80,"year":"1598","julianDay":2304718,"title":"Edict of Nantes ","description":"Under the rule of Henry IV of France the Edict of Nantes was issued giving the people some religious liberty. The edict brought an end to the religious wars that were going on at the time. ","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Edict-of-Nantes","urlTitle":"Encyclopedia Britannica- Edict of Nantes","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"John Arrow was born in 1518, in Ringstead, Northamptonshire, England. He married Jayne Nelson in 1539, in G